INSERT INTO public.diseases VALUES ('0', 'Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease', 'Persistent cough, difficulty breathing, increased mucus production, wheezing, chest tightness, fatigue, and frequent respiratory infections.', 'Quitting smoking is the most important step. Other treatments include bronchodilator medications, corticosteroids, pulmonary rehabilitation, oxygen therapy, and in severe cases, lung transplantation.', 'COPD is a chronic lung disease characterized by obstructed airflow, making it difficult to breathe. It usually includes chronic bronchitis and emphysema.', 'Smoking is the leading cause of COPD, but exposure to air pollution, occupational dust and chemicals, and genetic factors can also contribute.', ('1', 'Healthy', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', ('2', 'Upper Respiratory Tract Infection', 'Runny or stuffy nose, sore throat, cough, sneezing, congestion, headache, and mild body aches.', 'Rest, hydration, over-the-counter medications for symptom relief, such as decongestants or cough suppressants, and treating any underlying conditions, if applicable.', 'An upper respiratory tract infection is a common infection that affects the nose, throat, and other parts of the upper respiratory system.', 'Viruses, such as the common cold, are the most common cause of upper respiratory tract infections.', ('3', 'Bronchiectasis', 'Persistent cough with large amounts of mucus, recurrent respiratory infections, chest pain, wheezing, shortness of breath, and fatigue.', 'Antibiotics to treat infections, bronchodilators, chest physiotherapy, mucus-clearing techniques, and in some cases, surgery to remove damaged lung tissue.', 'Bronchiectasis is a chronic condition where the bronchial tubes in the lungs are permanently damaged and widened, leading to recurrent infections.', 'Infections, such as pneumonia or tuberculosis, and conditions that cause inflammation and damage to the airways, such as cystic fibrosis, are common causes of bronchiectasis.', ('4', 'Pneumonia', 'Fever, chills, cough with mucus or pus, chest pain, rapid or shallow breathing, difficulty breathing, fatigue, and confusion.', 'Antibiotics for bacterial pneumonia, antiviral or antifungal medications for viral or fungal pneumonia, oxygen therapy, and supportive care such as rest, fluids, and fever-reducing medication.', 'Pneumonia is an infection in the lungs that can be caused by bacteria, viruses, or fungi, leading to inflammation of the air sacs.', 'Bacterial, viral, or fungal infections, often triggered by respiratory tract infections or weakened immune systems, can cause pneumonia.', ('5', 'Bronchiolitis', 'Runny or stuffy nose, cough, rapid or difficulty breathing, wheezing, fever, poor feeding, irritability, and in severe cases, cyanosis (bluish coloration of lips or skin due to lack of oxygen).', 'Supportive care, including oxygen therapy, hydration, nasal suction, and close monitoring for signs of respiratory distress. In severe cases, hospitalization and additional interventions such as respiratory support and intravenous fluids may be needed. Medications such as bronchodilators, corticosteroids, and antibiotics are generally not effective for treating bronchiolitis, as it is primarily caused by viral infections.', 'Bronchiolitis is a viral infection that causes inflammation and swelling of the small airways (bronchioles) in the lungs, primarily affecting infants and young children.', 'Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) is the most common cause of bronchiolitis, although other viruses such as rhinovirus, human metapneumovirus, and others can also cause it.';